---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Acute Respiratory Distress" description="Simulation case for acute respiratory distress management.">
  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Acute Respiratory Distress</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Respiratory</span>
    <h1>Acute Respiratory Distress</h1>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>⏱ Duration: 40 minutes</span>
      <span>📊 Difficulty: Advanced</span>
      <span>👥 Team Size: 3–5</span>
      <span>🏥 Setting: Medical Ward / ICU</span>
    </div>
    <div class="tags" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <span class="tag">Critical Care</span>
      <span class="tag">Airway</span>
      <span class="tag">COPD</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Case Overview</h2>
    <p>
      A 72-year-old female, Mrs. Dorothy Simmons, with a known history of severe COPD (GOLD Stage III)
      experiences sudden deterioration in respiratory status on the general medicine ward. She is found
      sitting upright in bed, using accessory muscles, speaking in short sentences, and is increasingly
      confused.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learners must assess the severity of respiratory distress, identify the underlying cause
      (acute exacerbation of COPD with possible mucous plug), manage oxygenation and ventilation,
      and make the critical decision regarding non-invasive vs. invasive ventilation.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Patient Information</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Name:</strong> Dorothy Simmons</li>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong> 72 years</li>
      <li><strong>Gender:</strong> Female</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 62 kg</li>
      <li><strong>PMH:</strong> COPD (GOLD III), Hypertension, Osteoporosis</li>
      <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Tiotropium inhaler, Salmeterol/fluticasone inhaler, Amlodipine 5 mg</li>
      <li><strong>Allergies:</strong> NKDA</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Initial Vital Signs</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>BP:</strong> 138/86 mmHg</li>
      <li><strong>HR:</strong> 116 bpm (sinus tachycardia)</li>
      <li><strong>RR:</strong> 34 breaths/min</li>
      <li><strong>SpO₂:</strong> 82% on 2L nasal cannula</li>
      <li><strong>Temp:</strong> 38.3°C</li>
      <li><strong>GCS:</strong> 13 (confused)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul class="objective-list">
      <li>Rapidly assess and categorize severity of acute respiratory failure</li>
      <li>Differentiate between type I and type II respiratory failure using ABG interpretation</li>
      <li>Appropriately initiate controlled oxygen therapy in a COPD patient</li>
      <li>Initiate and titrate non-invasive positive pressure ventilation (BiPAP)</li>
      <li>Identify indications for endotracheal intubation and prepare for RSI</li>
      <li>Coordinate care with the respiratory therapy team and escalate to ICU</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Scenario Progression</h2>
    <h4>Phase 1 – Recognition (0–10 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Team responds to bedside call. Primary assessment reveals severe respiratory distress.
      ABG obtained shows hypercarbic respiratory failure (pH 7.28, pCO₂ 72, pO₂ 52).
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 2 – BiPAP Trial (10–25 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Bronchodilators administered, BiPAP initiated. Patient shows partial improvement
      but remains at risk for further deterioration.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 3 – Escalation (25–40 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Patient deteriorates requiring intubation decision. RSI medications selected and
      administered; post-intubation management initiated.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Debriefing Guide</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Was the severity of respiratory failure correctly identified and communicated?</li>
      <li>Was the ABG properly interpreted and used to guide management?</li>
      <li>Was BiPAP initiated appropriately with correct settings?</li>
      <li>How was the decision made to proceed to intubation?</li>
      <li>Was controlled oxygenation used to avoid hypercapnia worsening?</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <a href={`${base}cases/`} class="btn btn-primary" style="background: var(--color-primary); color: #fff;">← Back to Cases</a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
